use different method in different module.

comments.message: There are several violations of the Sierra Module Considerations confluence diagram on layers.  Can we remove those now?
Can we do it later when we build SWI code with Q6 compiler?  I don't want to touch Q6 scons file at this moment.

I defer to you guys as gatekeepers, but my preference would be to clean out the scons so that, even for dependencies that are in the valid layers, we aren't accidentally dragging along anything we don't need just by porting.  But if that's a different task, that's fine with me.  I left out the CWE scons altogether for the same reason.
I will remove target system's makefiles in this commit. They will be re-added when we start to integrate this package in SDX24 or SDX55.

As long as we're refactoring, please run something like
sed -i 's/[ \t]*$//' <file>
to remove the trailing whitespace throughout.

Please refer to my SWIMDM-1 review.  I think we should try to keep aaglobal_common.h as close to aligned with the original aaglobal.h as possible, to facilitate later comparison.  Much of the differences now are easily avoidable just be restoring the original order of the code.

aaglobal.h is very platform-depent, so inevitably there are many differences between Qualcomm Q6 and X86 Linux. I don't think we will be able to keep target aaglobal.h and UT aaglobal are closed. That's also why we had to additionally create another aaglobal.h for unit test.

AA has a lot of platform abstraction currently (sections depending on if the build is for Boot, Modem, Apss, etc).  I wonder if we could use the sierra/aa/ code directly if we add a compiler check for UTEST_ON_LINUX, and add our definitions there.  Of course if we need to add stubs in some cases, we may still need to amend that.  But something like the definition of PACKED_POST, for a specific environment, seems like a good thing to add to the original AA package as we're adding a new UT environment.

And it would need to supercede Modem/Boot/Apps definitions, since those could be enabled in the same build.  This could definitely be a side topic and not part of this ticket review, if not rejected altogether.

This is really a trade off. One point from Evan is that we should use UTEST_ON_LINUX in target code as few as possible, to avoid the UT dependencies of UT for target code. My thought is that we can prudently use UTEST_ON_LINUX in target code if it can really eliminate code duplicating.

Anyway, since your previous commit has defined PACKED_POST, I will just remove it in this commit.

I assume you're rerunning other tests to ensure they don't fail now, but this is why I think these doubles belong to the specific CUT, not globally.  We previously defined the double one way, and it was used in a test.  This change redefines the way that previous CUT is tested - what if the original test was to confirm handling of a NULL pointer returned in a mem_realloc call?
At this moment, no test cases are covering the cases where memory allocating is fail and we suppose memory allocating is always successful. We might add such test cases in future.

Yes, but this is still to my point.  Adding global test doubles doesn't seem like a safe approach, because anyone modifying the double needs to fully understand every use-case.  Also, every ut package pulls in the entire set of global doubles, which makes the scope very large.  I think it would be better to put doubles in the ut directory specific to the CUT that they are designed for.

Actually your new double for mem_realloc is basically an implementation that behaves similar to the original, just on a different platform.  But in other cases, the doubles return values very specific to a particular CUT.

I have different opinion about it. This test double implementation of mem_realloc can be global. We can extend this test double(and other memory functions) in future to meet all cases, like this:
- Add one flag (such as force_mem_failure) to control whether mem_realloc returns valid memoery block or NULL.
Under what conditions will this be removable?

comments.message: There is a side effect to add comdef.h in unit test. From new coding rule, we should use uint8_t/uint16_t.. to relace uint8/uint16... for all swi package code. But comdef.h explicitly defines uint8/uint16, that means if we use uint8/uin16 in swi code, the UT complier won't report any build error. That will lose one important check for UT test.
not used anywhere, although I'm not sure if we should remove it or not?
Removed, since I don't think it was even accurate.  CWE header revision implementation is at v3.  I'm not sure what 1 was referring to, if that was meant to be in sync.
should this be "const char const cwe_image_str" because both the pointer and strings are constant?
You're right, fixed.  I don't think I've ever used that before :).
Can we open a SWIMDM ticket for this?
Done, SWIMDM-20 (and will be updated in the comment)

Do you recall why we would stamp the header if the time was not set? From 9x15 4.5, it looks like we used it in bcfind() to make sure we returned the 'newest' CWE header that we were looking for. But I don't remember why we needed to do that.

Right, and we still do a basic comparison in newer code in nvup_core.c.  I discussed this briefly with Maggie, and I can't figure out why we would think we would be able to trust these timestamps anyway - half the time or more, their going to be based on the epoch and not a valid network time.  These are used for FLOG and for creating backups, both of which can be frequently seen on the system with epoch time, in practice.  

This change doesn't prevent the caller from setting the date, but it does introduce the potential that they won't, which is my only real concern.  We could abort without a date, but given that the date usually isn't useful in practice, that seems unwarranted.
Whether the code of one line is too long?
Thanks, I had a lot of these.  I hadn't turned on the margin checker for cpp in my editor.  Fixed, with a couple exceptions for single arguments that extend past the rule (long file names)
These definitions have been covered in some .h file, why we need to add them here again?

My understanding is that the TDD implementation of the test can't rely on the implementation file itself for these definitions.  This would make it very easy to implement the CWE header with incorrect fields - the implementation of the header file would directly affect the tests, and make detection of incorrect field definitions easy to miss.  This independant implementation of the spec makes the test more rigid, and also supports the TDD method of writing the test before the CUT.

The purpose of unit test is to test code logic, so we don't test such constant defintions in most cases. It's supposed that constant definitions are always expected, then we can use them as the criterias of unit test result. The correctness of constant definitions should be guaranteed by other way rather than unit test.

_package means this function can be called within the package(folder).
Is there any other test doble use zipglue_deflateEnd()?

We'd better to evaluate if it's worth to change them to thread-safe APIs.

These thread-unsafe functions have been called by multiple tasks(nv, data, pr) of modem and bootloader, so it has become a bug.

1. Keep it thread-unsafe, but only one modem task (such as nv task) is allowed to call it directly. Other tasks should send message to tell nv task to do zip operation.
2. Make it to thread-safe:
  2.1 Add mutex in zip functions to protect zip tcb.
  2.2 Or remove the global zip tcb, that mean each zip client owns its zip tcb respectively.

I prefer the 2.2 option because I think it's most clear.

why no function header for these two functions?

Even if is required we can do it more elegant way to let client to register for a zalloc function for example. So I think all these SWI_IMAGE_BOOT define code can be removed in this package and in this way we can also remove the dependency of bl.

QTISDX24-0033 - Add sync lock for spdecrypt/spencrypt

Root Cause
spdecrypt/spencrypt are thread-unsafe, but they are
needed to be called by multiple tasks.

Solution
Add sync lock for spdecrypt/spencrypt to make them
thread-safe.

Change-Id: I4bedf99d237b641cd08f8837864c68b7b0c6364b
Signed-off-by: Xin Wang <xwang@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: QTISDX24-0033 - Add sync lock for spdecrypt/spencrypt

comments.message: sp_init() shall be added to this part to indicate that it's thread-unsafe function.
The comment needs to be optimized once the design decision is made - dcl or current solution?
It's better to not use extern for global variables. Please see the comments in spuser.c.
Please always add void to indicate explicitely that there is no parameters.

singleton/double check lock can't be implemented with thread-safety with C/QC platform. os_mutex_init always needs one global mutex variable, but this global variable also needs another mutex protect for thread-safety, if we want to use singleton/double check lock. The key is that C doesn't have some similar "synchronized" mechanism in Java which can add sync lock without introducing any new global mutex variable.
Should we keep the same API naming style? spinit()?
I see most swi init functions are named with xxx_init. Basically I think xxx_init is more clear than xxxinit.
Generally it's true. The only thing I'm thinking is for a given package we'd better to use the same naming style.
Should we keep the same API naming style in this package? splock() & spunlock()?
